# SmartSphere Home System — Architecture Analysis & Planning

---

## 1. High-Level System Overview

SmartSphere is a **smart home automation simulator** with three tiers:

| Tier | Technology | Role |
|---|---|---|
| **Frontend** | Vercel (React/Next.js) | Dashboard UI — device control, monitoring, alerts |
| **Backend** | Render (Java Spring Boot) | Business logic, OOP simulation, REST API |
| **Database** | Supabase (PostgreSQL + Realtime) | Device state, logs, user config |

```mermaid
graph LR
    A["Browser (Vercel)"] -- REST / WebSocket --> B["Java Backend (Render)"]
    B -- SQL / Realtime --> C["Supabase (PostgreSQL)"]
    B -- File I/O --> D["Log Files (on Render)"]
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The Java backend on Render is the **single source of truth** for all device logic, OOP concepts, and multithreading. The frontend only renders state and sends commands.

---

## 2. Frontend Architecture

The dashboard hosted on **Vercel** should include these sections:

### 2.1 Dashboard Layout

| Section | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **Device Grid** | Cards for each device (Light, Fan, AC, DoorLock, Camera) with ON/OFF toggles and status indicators |
| **Automation Modes Panel** | Buttons for Night / Morning / Away modes with active-mode highlighting |
| **Energy Monitor** | Real-time bar/donut chart showing per-device and total power consumption |
| **Activity Log** | Scrollable, filterable timeline of device actions, mode changes, and alerts |
| **Alerts & Notifications** | Banner/toast area for security alerts, energy warnings, maintenance suggestions |
| **Device Health** | Usage-duration badges per device; maintenance warnings when thresholds are exceeded |

### 2.2 Page / Route Structure

```
/                → Dashboard (all sections above)
/devices         → Detailed device list & individual controls
/energy          → Full energy monitoring with historical graphs
/logs            → Complete activity log with search/filter
/settings        → Automation mode configuration, thresholds
```

### 2.3 Frontend–Backend Communication

- **REST API calls** (fetch/axios) for commands: toggle device, activate mode, get logs.
- **Supabase Realtime subscriptions** (or polling) for live device-state and alert updates pushed from the backend.

---

## 3. Backend Architecture

The Java backend on **Render** encapsulates **all OOP concepts** and business logic.

### 3.1 Module Breakdown

| Module | Responsibility | Key OOP Concepts |
|---|---|---|
| **Device Management** | CRUD and state control for all devices | Classes, Objects, Inheritance, Interfaces, Dynamic Method Dispatch |
| **Automation Engine** | Night / Morning / Away mode orchestration | Interfaces, Polymorphism |
| **Energy Monitor** | Calculate and track power consumption | Encapsulation, Exception Handling |
| **Logging System** | Persist every device action and event | File Handling, Packages |
| **Security System** | Detect anomalies, trigger alerts | Exception Handling, Multithreading |
| **Device Health Tracker** | Monitor usage duration, suggest maintenance | Constructors, Encapsulation |
| **Emergency Handler** | Fire/intrusion auto-response protocols | Exception Handling, Multithreading |
| **Predictive Energy Saver** | Suggest energy-saving actions when consumption is high | Encapsulation |

### 3.2 How Modules Communicate

```mermaid
graph TD
    API["REST Controller Layer"] --> DM["Device Manager"]
    API --> AE["Automation Engine"]
    API --> EM["Energy Monitor"]
    API --> LS["Logging System"]
    DM --> EM
    DM --> LS
    AE --> DM
    AE --> LS
    SS["Security System"] --> DM
    SS --> LS
    EH["Emergency Handler"] --> DM
    EH --> SS
    DHT["Device Health Tracker"] --> DM
    PES["Predictive Energy Saver"] --> EM
```

### 3.3 Multithreaded Device Simulation

Each device instance runs on its **own thread** to simulate real-world concurrent operation:

- A `DeviceThread` (extends `Thread` or implements `Runnable`) wraps each `Device` object.
- Threads periodically update device state (e.g., energy tick, health counter).
- The Security System thread monitors device states for anomalies.
- `synchronized` blocks or `ConcurrentHashMap` protect shared device state.

---

## 4. Device Class Hierarchy

### 4.1 Design

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Controllable {
        <<interface>>
        +turnOn() void
        +turnOff() void
        +getStatus() String
    }
    class EnergyConsumer {
        <<interface>>
        +getPowerUsage() double
    }
    class Device {
        <<abstract>>
        -String deviceId
        -String name
        -boolean isOn
        -double powerRating
        -long usageDuration
        +Device(id, name, powerRating)
        +turnOn() void
        +turnOff() void
        +getStatus() String
        +getPowerUsage() double
        +performAction(action)* void
    }
    Controllable <|.. Device
    EnergyConsumer <|.. Device
    Device <|-- Light
    Device <|-- Fan
    Device <|-- AC
    Device <|-- DoorLock
    Device <|-- SecurityCamera

    class Light {
        -int brightness
        +setBrightness(level) void
        +performAction(action) void
    }
    class Fan {
        -int speed
        +setSpeed(level) void
        +performAction(action) void
    }
    class AC {
        -double temperature
        +setTemperature(temp) void
        +performAction(action) void
    }
    class DoorLock {
        -boolean isLocked
        +lock() void
        +unlock() void
        +performAction(action) void
    }
    class SecurityCamera {
        -boolean isRecording
        +startRecording() void
        +stopRecording() void
        +performAction(action) void
    }
```

### 4.2 OOP Concept Mapping

| Concept | Where It Appears |
|---|---|
| **Classes & Objects** | `Device`, `Light`, `Fan`, `AC`, `DoorLock`, `SecurityCamera` — each instantiated per room/device |
| **Constructors** | `Device(id, name, powerRating)` — parameterized constructor in abstract base, called via `super()` in subclasses |
| **Inheritance** | `Light extends Device`, `Fan extends Device`, etc. |
| **Interfaces** | `Controllable` (on/off), `EnergyConsumer` (power usage) — implemented by `Device` |
| **Dynamic Method Dispatch** | `Device d = new Light(...); d.performAction("dim");` — resolved at runtime to `Light.performAction()` |
| **Packages** | `com.smartsphere.devices`, `com.smartsphere.automation`, `com.smartsphere.energy`, `com.smartsphere.security`, `com.smartsphere.logging` |
| **Exception Handling** | `InvalidDeviceActionException`, `DeviceNotFoundException`, `EnergyThresholdExceededException` |
| **Multithreading** | `DeviceThread` per device, `SecurityMonitorThread`, `EnergyMonitorThread` |
| **File Handling** | `ActivityLogger` writes to `logs/activity.log`; optionally synced to Supabase |

---

## 5. Data Flow

### 5.1 User Toggles a Device

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as User (Browser)
    participant F as Frontend (Vercel)
    participant B as Backend (Render)
    participant DB as Supabase

    U->>F: Clicks "Turn ON Light"
    F->>B: POST /api/devices/{id}/toggle
    B->>B: DeviceManager.toggleDevice(id) → polymorphic call
    B->>DB: UPDATE devices SET is_on=true
    B->>B: ActivityLogger.log("Light turned ON")
    B->>B: EnergyMonitor.recalculate()
    B-->>F: 200 OK { device state }
    F-->>U: UI updates (light card shows ON)
```

### 5.2 Automation Mode Activation

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant F as Frontend
    participant B as Backend
    participant DB as Supabase

    F->>B: POST /api/modes/activate { mode: "NIGHT" }
    B->>B: AutomationEngine.activate(NIGHT)
    B->>B: Iterates devices → dim lights, lock doors, start cameras
    B->>DB: Batch UPDATE device states
    B->>B: ActivityLogger.log("Night Mode activated")
    B-->>F: 200 OK { updated device states }
```

### 5.3 Security Alert

```
SecurityMonitorThread detects: door unlocked during Away Mode
  → SecuritySystem.triggerAlert("Unauthorized door access")
    → ActivityLogger.log(alert)
    → Supabase INSERT into alerts table
    → Frontend picks up alert via Realtime subscription → shows notification
```

---

